Let G be a finite group, B a block of characters of G, D(B) its defect group and k(B) (respectively, k0(B)) the number of all irreducible complex characters (of height 0) lying in B. Conjectures:
a) (R. Brauer)
k(B) ⩽|D(B)|; this has been proved for p-soluble groups (D. Gluck, K. Magaard, U. Riese, P. Schmid, J. Algebra, 279 (2004), 694–719);
b) (J. B. Olsson) k0(B) ⩽|D(B) : D(B)′|, where D(B)′ is the derived subgroup of D(B);
c) (R. Brauer) D(B) is abelian if and only if k0(B) = k(B).
V. D. Mazurov
